The crystal formations in this region contain data in their
molecular structure. I've discovered that different types of
crystals store different data types. This simple test program
helped me identify the basic data types used in Chronovyan.

// Chronovyan Learning Example: Basic Data Types
// Difficulty: Beginner
// Concepts: Variables, data types, conditionals, output
//
// This example demonstrates the fundamental data types and operations
// in Chronovyan that Alex might use to process environmental data
// collected by CORA during exploration.

// Numeric data - integers
whole_number = 42  // A simple integer value

// Text data - strings
message = "Hello, Chronovyan!"  // A string of characters

// Variable assignment and storage
data_reading = 10  // Store the value 10 in a variable

// Conditional logic with data modification
if (data_reading > 5) {
    // This condition is true, so this code will execute
    print_to_cora("Reading is greater than threshold")
    data_reading = data_reading + 1  // Increment the value
}

// Different data types for environmental readings
temperature = 23.5  // Decimal number (float) for precision
is_safe_zone = true  // Boolean value (true/false)
location_name = "Crystal Cavern"  // Text description (string)

// Output the readings with string concatenation
print_to_cora("Temperature: " + temperature + " degrees")
print_to_cora("Safe Zone: " + is_safe_zone)
print_to_cora("Location: " + location_name)
print_to_cora("Updated Reading: " + data_reading)

// Basic arithmetic operations
energy_available = 85
energy_used = 35
energy_remaining = energy_available - energy_used
print_to_cora("Energy Remaining: " + energy_remaining)

// Multiplication and division
samples_per_hour = 6
hours_of_operation = 8
total_samples = samples_per_hour * hours_of_operation
print_to_cora("Total samples to collect: " + total_samples)

// Demonstrating more complex expressions
resource_density = 3.7
extraction_efficiency = 0.85
expected_yield = resource_density * extraction_efficiency * total_samples
print_to_cora("Expected resource yield: " + expected_yield + " units")

/*
This simple program demonstrates the fundamental data types
used in Chronovyan code: numbers (integers and decimals),
strings (text), and booleans (true/false values).

The ability to store different types of data is crucial for
environmental analysis. Each crystal type appears to store
a specific type of data, which must be accessed and processed
differently. This will be essential for calibrating our
sensing equipment to local conditions.
*/

